  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve steak wine at room temperature or slightly chilled?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve full-bodied reds like Cabernet Sauvignon at 60-65°F, which is slightly cooler than room temperature—this temperature enhances the wine's structure and prevents alcohol from overwhelming the palate. If your dining room is warm, chill the bottle for 15-20 minutes before serving, as overly warm wine will taste flabby and lose its ability to cut through the steak's richness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibelier text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine should I choose for grilled versus pan-seared steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled steaks develop smoky, charred flavors that pair beautifully with robust wines like Argentine Malbec, Australian Shiraz, or Rhône blends that have earthy, peppery notes. Pan-seared steaks have a more concentrated, caramelized crust that works well with structured Bordeaux blends or Italian Sangiovese, which complement the Maillard reaction flavors without competing with smoke.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is steak wine pairing suitable for beginners, or should I start with lighter dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Steak and red wine is actually an excellent pairing for beginners because it demonstrates fundamental wine principles clearly—the protein and fat in steak soften harsh tannins, making bold wines more approachable. Start with crowd-pleasing combinations like Cabernet Sauvignon with ribeye or Malbec with NY strip, which are forgiving and showcase how food transforms wine.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wine based solely on the cut of steak while ignoring the preparation and sauce—a filet with béarnaise sauce needs a different wine than the same cut with just salt and pepper. Additionally, many people select wines that are too young and tannic, forgetting that even bold steaks can be overwhelmed by overly aggressive wines that haven't had time to integrate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good non-red wine alternatives for steak pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Full-bodied white wines like aged Chardonnay from Burgundy or Rhône white blends can pair surprisingly well with lighter cuts like filet mignon, especially when prepared with cream sauces. For adventurous pairers, try a rich Champagne or Crémant with salt-and-pepper seasoned steak—the bubbles cut through fat while the wine's weight matches the meat's intensity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose an affordable wine that still pairs well with expensive steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for value-driven regions like Washington State Cabernet Sauvignon, Portuguese Douro reds, or Spanish Jumilla—these areas produce structured, age-worthy wines at a fraction of the cost of Napa or Bordeaux. A $15-20 bottle from these regions often delivers the tannin structure and flavor intensity needed to complement premium steak cuts without breaking the bank.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I open the wine before serving with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Open full-bodied reds 30-60 minutes before serving to allow tannins to soften and aromatics to develop—this is especially important for young Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo that might taste harsh when first opened. For older wines (10+ years), decant immediately before serving to avoid over-oxidation, while mid-range wines benefit from breathing time to show their best alongside rich steak flavors.</p>
